Although the clause itself seems a reasonable defense, isn't it
rather dangerous to rely on judges to determine whether the
patent is "applicable to software"? 

Say we have a patent on an audio coding technique, and the patent
has a claim on a chip and on a computer program. Is this a "patent
applicable to software", and does the clause apply if we assert
this patent against someone whose chips infringe our patent?

How about:
If you institute patent litigation against a Contributor alleging
that a computer program by itself infringes on a patent (including a
cross-claim or counterclaim in a lawsuit), then any patent licenses
granted by that Contributor to You under this License shall terminate as
of the date such litigation is filed.

