Not at all, it's worthwhile to delve into this.  Hope to meet you "live" 
at ApacheCon.  "Contribution" is defined as the original work of 
authorship or any additions or modifications submitted for that 
inclusion to that Work (with "Work" being defined simply as the work of 
authorship to which this License is attached).  Thus, if someone alleged 
that an entire Work constituted patent infringement, that party would 
lose any and all patent licenses granted to it under the License for 
that Work, which would include the individual patent licenses granted by 
the Contributors under Section 4 for their Contributions that had been 
submitted for inclusion in that Work..  Note the corresponding language 
in the proposed Contributor License Agreement, which states: "Your [the 
Contributor] patent grant shall terminate with respect to any party that 
institutes patent litigation against you (including a cross-claim or 
counterclaim in a lawsuit) alleging that your Contribution, or the work 
to which you have contributed, constitutes direct or contributory patent 
infringement, as of the date such litigation is filed."


