Eben Moglen wrote:
> 	1.  Why is it that we don't presently observe instances of the
>             problem we are trying to solve?  Patent infringement
>             lawsuits have not been brought against free software
>             programs, though there are lots of software patents and a
>             certain serious number of infringement actions.  

The reason is simple: patent litigation is *extremely* expensive
(expect over a million in fees and other costs). You simply Do Not
sue people for patent infringement if the value of the suit is
less than that. Most open source developers are not multi-million
dollar entities, and so you simply can't expect to recover your
costs.

This might change if a company wishes to stop a certain open source
project and happens to have a lot of cash sitting around. I don't
know of many such companies.

>Is the
>             non-occurrence simply an artifact of probability, or are
>             there existing social and legal mechanisms that already
>             establish a gradient against such actions, a form of
>             "natural immunity" which our licensing or other
>             defense arrangements might act to strengthen?

Another issue is the low visibility of open source amongst most
patent holders, together with a lack of awareness that open
source licenses have patent clauses. It's not trivial to see that 
the GPL has a mandatory RF patent license clause, for example.

Next, there's the large amount of negative publicity you will
get if you announce you will sue an open source project. 

But I still think the most important reason is that open source
simply isn't on the radar screens in most patent departments.
For most companies, this will not change until a big competitor
puts open source in their products which infringes on the
company's patents. Then the company will sue, upon which the
competitor will counter with "But you distributed that same
open source under GPL a year ago".

That's about the only scenario I can think of where patents
and open source will conflict. And it assumes the big competitor
will use open source for important technology, that the two
companies do not have a cross license, and so on.

> 	2.  If I am a patent-holder wishing to sue some part of the
>             free software ecology for patent infringement, either in
>             order to obtain license revenue or in order to disrupt the
>             free software system, couldn't I build a separated special
>             purpose entity that would hold the relevant patent(s) and
>             conduct the litigation, thus insulating my main businesses
>             from the retaliatory effect of license cancellations?

You will want to keep control over the patent or the separate
business unit that will sue with it. Otherwise, how are you going
to ensure you get the benefits from the lawsuit back? 

And if you have effective control, it's not really a separate
entity anymore. 

Still, it might work in some cases. If one business unit uses
GPL-licensed software, that unit is the "You" in the license
and must stick to its terms. If the patents are owned by another
business unit (both under the umbrella of the mother company),
then the patent business unit is not bound by the GPL, because
the GPL does not have a clause that defines "You" to include
affiliated companies. Perhaps it should.

Perhaps I should state at this point I'm a patent attorney working
for a big company. The above is purely my own opinion of course.

