Under the AFL, patents from licensor (contributors *or* distributors) =
are
licensed to all royalty-free.  [See =A7 2.]  Your scenario wouldn't =
happen if
you used the AFL as both your contributors' license and your =
distribution
license.  The AFL =A7 2 prevents anyone from "sneaking code into the =
codebase
covered by their own patent and then seeking royalties" for it.  Section =
2
of the AFL deals with the licensor's patents. =20

As for the AFL patent termination provision [=A7 10], it deals with a =
very
different situation, where a licensee claims patent infringement of his =
own
patent -- either his patent relating to any software [=A7 10(a)] or his =
patent
relating to the licensed software [=A7 10(b)].  Section 10 of the AFL =
deals
with the licensee's patents.

By the way, please don't refer to =A7 10 as a "mutual defense" =
provision.
Largely at HP's suggestion [thanks, Scott!] the new versions of the AFL =
&
OSL licenses don't use mutual defense language any more. =20

The discussion today is about a provision similar in form and effect to =
the
IBM (and Mozilla, and Apple, and Nokia, and etc.) patent termination
language.  My point -- and Scott's -- is that typical open source =
license
patent defense provisions that terminate only the licensor's patent =
grants
are useless to any licensor (project or contributor) that doesn't own =
any
patents.  The only meaningful threat is to terminate both the licensor's
patent licenses [the license grant in AFL =A7 2] as well as the =
licensor's
copyright licenses [the license grant in AFL =A7 1].  That is what AFL =
=A7 10
does, and what the proposed Apache license doesn't do.

Scott is correct in characterizing this as an important consideration =
for
licensees of open source software.  (Scott calls it a "risk" and Russ =
calls
it a "decision"; I agree with Russ.)  I happen to believe that our =
software
is worth more than the possible value a licensee might receive from
asserting a software patent against an open source licensor or =
contributor.

